{"type":"message","id":"8bb459e3","parentId":"41583824","timestamp":"2026-02-17T13:19:23.715Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Confirming Timeouts Effectively**\n\nI've just confirmed `yieldMs`'s functionality. I used a 65-second timeout with a 60-second sleep command, and it behaved as expected, successfully returning within the specified timeframe. I'm now exploring how it handles longer-running operations.\n\n\n**Revising Timeout Parameters**\n\nI've made a crucial correction! Initially, I mistakenly assumed the `echo` command was the primary operation, leading to an incorrect assessment of `yieldMs`. It turns out I had chained commands with `sleep` calls. The first command, `sleep 900`, started around 13:10 and is still running. My current tests involve sleep intervals ranging from 300 to 780 seconds. I'm now refocusing on the relationship between `yieldMs` and the actual command execution times.\n\n\n**Refining Command Sequencing**\n\nI've finally pinpointed the flaw in my testing methodology. I was inadvertently timing the wrong part of the command chain. I now understand that my immediate return was due to the instant execution of `echo`. I've corrected my approach and am now using `sleep` calls to accurately gauge `yieldMs`. I'm currently running a test with `sleep 360` and `yieldMs: 370000` to confirm my findings and expect the process to block for six minutes. Afterwards, I will check the file.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771334363703_400","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"sleep 360","yieldMs":370000},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-gemini-cli","provider":"google-gemini-cli","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":1344,"output":516,"cacheRead":9404,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":11264,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771334354835}}
